<TEXT>
president roh taewoo fired his 
defense minister and the powerful chief of military intelligence 
today blaming them in a scandal involving charges the government 
spied on more than 1300 civilians 
opposition leader kim daejung one alleged target of the 
espionage joined student protesters in calling for the 
intelligence units dissolution 
dissidents said the scandal proves the undemocratic nature 
of rohs government 
charges in the past week of military surveillance of civilians 
including leading politicians have eroded government claims that 
the military is politically neutral and no longer a figure in 
politics 
presidential spokesman lee soojung said roh was holding the two 
fired officials responsible in the scandal he said the government 
would enact reforms to meet with circumstances befitting the new 
era but did not elaborate 
roh moved quickly in an effort to diminish the impact of the 
scandal it threatened to seriously jolt his government just as 
opposition politicians have boycotted the national assembly 
demanding broader democratic reforms 
in august all 78 opposition members of parliament resigned en 
masse accusing roh of railroading bills and ignoring demands for 
reforms 
defense minister lee sanghoon was being replaced immediately by 
former army chief of staff lee jongkoo 57 lt gen koo changhoe 
is new commander of the defense security command the military 
intelligence unit replacing lt gen cho nampung the presidents 
office said 
the new defense minister once headed the defense security 
command under disgraced former president chun doohwan chun has 
been in selfimposed rural exile to take responsibility for 
corruption during his sevenyear rule which ended in 1988 after 
massive studentled street protests 
kim daejung who heads the opposition party for peace and 
democracy and had been imprisoned for political activity during 
chuns rule said today that he would go on a hunger strike until 
the command is dissolved 
the militarys meddling in politics aims at wiping out the 
democratic forces he told a news conference 
about 25 students shouting antigovernment slogans staged a 
sitdown protest today at the defense security command headquarters 
near the us 8th army base in central seoul all were taken away 
by riot police 
about 50 students staged a onehour protest outside seoul 
national university to demand the command be disbanded wallposters 
demanding an end to political surveillance appeared on the campuses 
of at least six universities 
newspapers published reports saying military intelligence agents 
had in the past received passes to drive onto some campuses and 
operated offcampus coffee houses masquerading as waiters 
about 100 dissidents representing 20 leading antigovernment 
groups issued a joint statement today saying the political 
surveillance proves the immorality and undemocratic nature of the 
present regime 
the fired defense minister appeared to try to shed blame for the 
scandal by suggesting he had been powerless to control the 
intelligence unit he told reporters the system should be changed 
to give the minister complete control over military intelligence 
politicians citizens groups lawyers and dissidents reacted in 
outrage last week after a deserter 24yearold army pvt yoon 
sukyang disclosed the alleged surveillance of civilians in this 
nation of 425 million people 
rohs political foes demanded that he apologize publicly that 
the command be dissolved and that measures be spelled out to 
prevent further surveillance 
yoon deserted from the military intelligence operation on sept 
23 taking with him confidential papers computer discs and data he 
said were evidence of massive and organized illegal spying on 
civilians 
he provided data that included the names and personal records of 
governing party chairman kim youngsam kim daejung and 89 other 
lawmakers as well as hundreds of dissidents clergy and 
journalists 
the defense ministry said saturday it kept the information not 
for political surveillance but to protect or cut off those listed 
from enemies or impure elements 
roh promised to maintain the militarys political neutrality 
after taking office in 1988 
he took control of two thirds of the 299 national assembly seats 
in january by merging his party with two conservative opposition 
groups 
</TEXT>
