<TEXT>
the soldiers of britains 7th 
armored brigade the desert rats of north africa fame have 
been assigned to us marine control in an unusual pairing in the 
persian gulf multinational forces 
officials say that in the event of war the 7000 british troops 
would fight as an integral unit of the 4th marine expeditionary 
brigade relying on marine air support and using natotype 
communications gear 
both sides appear to welcome the teaming despite their 
contrasting skills 
the 33000 marines trained primarily as an amphibious assault 
force using helicopters and landing craft have been in the saudi 
sand for six weeks 
the 7th brigade despite its desert legacy has spent much of 
the last 40 years in the green fields of western europe 
the british brigades two regiments recently spent some time 
training in hot dry terrain in canada but conditions there hardly 
compare with what the british will find in the saudi desert with 
its extreme heat and equipmentravaging sand 
advance parties of the brigade are already in saudi arabia and 
royal engineers are building a tent city located close to the 
marine base to be ready when the main force begins to arrive by 
air on oct 16 
the units equipment including 120 advanceddesign challenger 
tanks will be sent aboard 31 chartered ships british officials 
say 
the challengers fitted with 120mm main guns and what british 
experts call the worlds best armor are superior to anything the 
iraqis have british armed forces minister archibald hamilton 
said during a vist on saturday 
hamilton the secondranking official in britains defense 
ministry told reporters that the idea of putting the 7th brigade 
under marine operational control originated with the americans as a 
way of enhancing the capability of the marines 
we welcome it agreed a marine officer who asked not to be 
named everybody will keep their national identity but 
tactically the brits will be just another maneuver element in our 
force 
us officers say the marines will furnish the air cover for the 
7th brigade as well as their own troops the british will be 
responsible for their own logistics resupply and transportation 
</TEXT>
