<TEXT>
once again the government finds itself on the 
financial precipice because of the inability of a republican white 
house and a democratic congress to agree to a solution to the 
worsening deficit problem 
here are answers to some frequently asked questions about the 
impact of budget stalemate on americans 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
q why is the federal government forced to shut down 
a because the budget dispute prevented enactment of any of the 
13 regular appropriations bills for fiscal 1991 the federal budget 
year that began oct 1 the constitution states that no money 
shall be drawn from the treasury but in consequence of 
appropriations made by law while some appropriations are in 
permanent law most daytoday government operations are renewed 
annually in one of the 13 spending bills 
what that means is that government agencies are not allowed to 
spend money including for salaries or purchases unless there is a 
law authorizing them to do so since there wasnt even a stopgap 
law in place saturday the agencies were legally required to send 
people home and close down 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
q has this ever happened before 
a yes similar squabbles have forced the government to shut 
down temporarily three times in the past decade 
it happened briefly in november 1981 when an estimated 400000 
employees were dismissed at midday after president reagan vetoed an 
emergency money bill on oct 4 1984 about 500000 government 
workers were sent home by congress failure to approve an 
appropriations bill 
and on oct 16 1986 the government sent 500000 
nonessential employees home but congress later in the day 
passed an appropriations bill acceptable to reagan and workers were 
ordered to report on their next shift 
congress as it had done in 1981 and 1984 passed a resolution 
ordering that employees furloughed get their regular salaries 
anyway 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
q what is this grammrudman act i keep hearing so much 
about and why was it passed 
a congress enacted the law named for sens phil gramm 
rtexas and warren rudman rnh in 1985 and revised it in 1987 
in passing the law congress in effect admitted that it could 
not make the tough choices needed to halt deficit spending without 
some outside pressure to force them into it 
the law requires congress and the president to reduce the 
deficit to predetermined annual targets leading eventually to a 
balanced budget if the targets are missed the law requires 
acrosstheboard spending cuts to do the job congress could not 
the target for fiscal 1991 is 64 billion but the presidents 
estimates are so far above that number that bush and congress agree 
it is impossible to reach they will change it to a much higher 
number if they agree on an overall budget package the result 
will be to delay the goal of a balanced budget probably until 1996 
or beyond 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
q what events prompted the current shutdown 
a on sept 30 the last day of fiscal 1990 bush and the 
bipartisan congressional leadership announced agreement on a 
fiveyear 500 billion deficitreduction package that included 
approximately 134 billion in new taxes congress passed and bush 
signed a oneweek temporary appropriations bill to keep the 
government operating while congress passed the plan bush went on 
national television tuesday night to appeal for congressional 
support of the package but it was decisively voted down thursday 
night 
members of the house and senate approved another stopgap 
spending measure known as a continuing resolution on friday 
that would have kept the government running until friday oct 12 
and would have given lawmakers another weeks time to arrive at a 
budget consensus but bush vetoed that bill saturday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
q how will the shutdown affect me can i still catch my flight 
for example 
a the government began closing socalled nonessential 
facilities saturday including parks and tourist attractions but 
air traffic controllers are among those considered essential 
however if the deadlock persisted there would be a reduction in 
the number of controllers allowed to work 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
q what is meant by essential and nonessential 
a each agency decides what is an essential service but 
generally staying on the job will be workers dealing with national 
security health emergency and similar things the military air 
traffic controllers border guards medical institution personnel 
and prison guards will be unaffected federal meat and poultry 
inspection will continue during a general shutdown 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

