<DOCNO> AP901008-0064 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mayor david dinkins said today that whatever his 
new beds headboard cost and it reportedly cost 11500 the 
city will not pay a penny of it 
the mayor said he has instructed city officials to find out by 
tuesday whether it really took 11500 for a city carpenter to 
duplicate a headboard that would have cost 1600 in a store 
whatever the explanation the city will not pay a single penny 
of the cost dinkins said in a statement issued by his press 
secretary albert scardino it will all be covered by private 
donations from friends of the city many of whom have contacted me 
this morning to offer their contributions 
dinkins was stung by a newsweek magazine story about the 
headboard which came days after the citys money woes prompted the 
mayor to freeze hiring propose new taxes and raise the possibility 
of laying off 15000 city employees 
dinkins said the headboard was delivered to gracie mansion the 
mayors official residence on friday it was built to match other 
pieces of a bedroom set that dinkins said he paid for himself 
i wish somebody would ask me why dont i seek reimbursement 
for the 8000 or 9000 i spent on the bedroom suite no questions 
have come to me in that regard i contributed that he said 
sunday at the pulaski day parae 
dinkins statement said the city had received contributions of 
1400 toward the cost of the bed 
earlier scardino said materials for the headboard cost 1400 
and that it was paid for by the gracie mansion conservancy a 
private nonprofit organization labor cost should have added up to 
an additional few hundred dollars at most scardino said 
the headboard was built by anthony russo a carpenter on the 
staff of the citys human resources administration newsweek said 
he has submitted bills for 266 hours of labor at a cost to date 
of 648412 according to a work order obtained by newsweek two 
hra sources told newsweek the complete job is expected to total 500 
hours at a cost of 23 an hour or 11500 
the dinkinses chose a cherrywood set and bought nightstands and 
bureaus from a private company with their own money for 8000 
officials said the matching headboard had been discontinued by the 
company so the conservancy agreed to buy the materials to build 
one 
scardino speculated the bill that newsweek obtained might 
actually have been for a series of jobs 
its possible this bill represents many jobs thats the only 
way to explain it because theres no possible way the labor cost 
of the headboard could be more than the rest of the furniture 
bought for the room he said 
