<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901008-0070 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
for the past several years the us commerce 
department approved export licenses for american companies to ship 
technology to iraq that could be used against us troops a 
newspaper reported 
the commerce department was largely unhindered in its drive to 
promote trade with south africa libya iraq and iran the 
cleveland plain dealer reported in articles sunday and today 
pentagon and other government officials with expertise about 
weapons and national security interests were routinely kept in the 
dark about many usmade exports they say now threaten american 
troops the newspaper reported 
if the exports are in the gray area of dual use chances are 
we dont even know about it said william n rudman the 
pentagons deputy undersecretary for trade security policy 
if the pentagon has suspicions about a deal it has no legal 
authority to stop the shipment it would be up to the state 
department to do so he said 
they commerce department wanted to push as much stuff out 
the door as they could said stephen bryen a former pentagon 
trade security official 
the newspaper said that from 1984 until just months before 
saddam husseins invasion of kuwait the commerce department 
approved at least 15 licenses to export tens of millions of dollars 
in equipment and technology that intelligence specialists believe 
could be used to help pack iraqs arsenals 
among the licenses were ones allowing us businesses to sell 
iraq mainframe computers useful in designing and plotting the 
course of missiles and to sell furnaces that could melt and cast 
nuclear materials 
the newspaper said that in 1987 the commerce department agreed 
to allow a new jersey company electronics associates inc to sell 
a halfmilliondollar analog computer system to iraq it was 
similar to one at the white sands missile range in new mexico the 
companys brochure had a photo of a missile on the cover 
the pentagons office of national trade security protested the 
sale but the computer was shipped anyway the newspaper said 
at least twice executives at another new jersey company 
consarc corp themselves raised the possibility that iraq intended 
to buy the companys furnaces and computers for nuclear purposes 
instead of for their stated purposes of making knee joints and 
artificial hips 
in july just as the furnace was about to be loaded onto a ship 
in philadelphia president bush blocked the shipment 
paul freedenberg former head of export controls for the 
commerce department defended the departments decisions saying 
that toozealous blocking of exports would erode the united states 
competitive edge and that iran south africa or others would get 
