<TEXT>
when a slum in the nations secondlargest 
city burst into violence last week a raw sore was exposed in this 
country proud of its social order and growing affluence 
during the nearly weeklong street violence in the airin district 
that eased sunday the face of a largely hidden underclass finally 
emerged it is a group of outcasts who feel abused by the rest of 
society particularly the police and gangsters who so closely 
monitor their lives 
you can never understand this feeling a 50yearold laborer 
lying on a park bench shouted at a visitor during the height of the 
rioting how do you know what it is like to be treated like the 
dregs of society everyone treats us as if we are less than human 
so go away 
airin which means love your neighbor is considered 
japans largest slum more than 90 percent of its 25000 residents 
are day laborers 
at first glance the district looks like an ordinary 
neighborhood but on closer examination one quickly discovers 
airin is a world apart from the rest of japan 
drunken men sleep on the dirty streets the stench of urine and 
garbage is pervasive barracks made of cardboard boxes fill the 
local park shabby hotels that charge 770 a night do a booming 
business 
airins day laborers are among the poorest people in this 
economic superpower supplying the manpower for local construction 
jobs they are japans unfortunates farmers and businessmen who 
went bust minorities facing discrimination family outcasts and 
exconvicts 
reports that a police official was suspected of taking 84600 
in bribes from gangsters who control the labor market touched off 
the riot 
angered workers who see themselves as victims of both police 
and the gangsters quickly massed in front of the local police 
station and were soon stoning police 
in following days the crowds set fire to automobiles looted 
stores and waged pitched street battles with the 2500 riot police 
in violence rarely seen in japan nearly 200 people mostly police 
were injured more than 50 were arrested airin was quiet for a 
second day monday 
allegations of police corruption in osaka are not unusual but 
the airin residents are particularly angered by allegations of 
police collusion with the gangsters known as yakuza who control 
the daily recruiting of laborers for construction companies 
sen arimura who works at the districts job placement center 
says part of the money construction companys allot for workers 
salary which is usually no more than minimum wage eventually 
winds up in the pockets of recruiters many of whom belong to the 
mob 
for example laborers often spend much of their earnings on 
gambling a stronghold of the yakuza and end up with huge debts 
many of the popular cheap bars and pachinko parlors the 
japanese version of pinball halls in the area are also run by 
gangsters 
