<TEXT>
world chess champion garry kasparovs defense of 
his title against blood rival anatoly karpov is a 3 million war of 
personalities politics and playing styles 
the two went head to head monday night at the hudson theatre in 
manhattan where some 700 seats for the opening match were sold out 
at 25 50 and 100 each the first match of the championship 
began at 530 pm 
kasparov 27 ended karpovs 10year world chess reign in 1985 
now karpov 39 is trying to wrest the title back as the nemeses 
meet for the first time in three years 
it is the first world championship in the united states since 
1907 after the first 12 games are played in new york 12 more will 
be played in lyon france beginning nov 24 
for the new york showdown the theater is hung with the flags of 
the united states france and the soviet union home country of 
both players 
above the stage is a 10foot screen bearing the image of a chess 
board when kasparov or karpov makes a move the pieces on the 
screen move too for the audiences benefit 
two video screens show closeups of the players the 
computerized chess board will record every move they make 
the board is atop a stark black table with two name tags 
pasted on the front 
one labeled a karpov depicts the soviet flag next to the 
table is karpovs black highbacked easy chair which swivels and 
rolls 
on the opposite side is a black lowbacked officestyle chair 
that side is labeled g kasparov with a depiction of the flag 
of the russian republic 
kasparov founder of a soviet democratic party declared last 
week he was playing under the flag of the republic rather than the 
soviet union as a political statement karpov often has been quoted 
as saying i have two loves communism and chess 
normally chess is a battle between two individuals a brutal 
intellectual battle kasparov said earlier but in my case 
with karpov its a fight between two different mentalities in 
russia i identify him with the system ive been fighting 
years ago a chess analyst likened kasparovs agile bold style 
to the dancer mikhail baryshnikov and karpovs methodical rigid 
style to former soviet premier leonid brezhnev 
the two are as different in personality as they are in political 
leanings 
kasparov who beat deep thought a chessplaying computer 
in new york last january is confident flamboyant and fluent in 
english a media darling who tirelessly publicizes chess 
the media have often described karpov as cool or even cold an 
introvert who plays with surgical precision and tunes out the 
audience but he was personable at a news conference last tuesday 
hamming it up and presenting a copy of his book to kasparov 
the first championship between the two in 1984 was abruptly 
helted by the world chess federation president after karpov lost 
two games in a row in a controversial move the world chess 
federation permitted karpov to retain the title although the match 
wasnt completed 
kasparov won their 1985 rematch becoming the youngest champion 
ever he successfully defended the title against karpov in 1986 in 
1987 their championship match ended in a tie and kasparov retained 
his title under the match rules 
this time the winner will receive 17 million and the loser 
will get 13 million kasparov aid his earnings will fund my 
private interests and the political interests of the world 
karpov has talked about helping chernobyl victims and promoting 
chess in schools 
