<TEXT>
parliaments upper house on monday ratified 
the sixnation treaty restoring german sovereignty and chancellor 
helmut kohl asked for rapid help in rebuilding the eastern part of 
the newly united nation 
the bundesrat also gave final approval to a law enabling 
national elections to be held dec 2 
the treaty formally ends special rights in germany of the four 
world war ii victors the united states the soviet union britain 
and france it was ratified without opposition in the bundesrat 
three days after it was approved by the lower house the bundestag 
the document was signed on sept 12 in moscow by the wartime 
allies and the two germanys 
the new election law replaces an earlier agreement ruled 
unconstitutional by the suprem court in effect the law sets up 
two separate election areas in germany one in former west germany 
and one in nowdefunct east germany 
the rejected law would have required parties to win at least 5 
percent across germany for seats in the bundestag under the new 
law parties need to win only 5 percent in either former east 
germany or west germany 
kohl convened a summit of germanys most powerful business 
leaders monday to issue a personal appeal for quick help in 
rebuilding former east germany 
i have a completely personal request to make of you he told 
the assemblage at the chancellery 
think over the contribution you and your workers can offer so 
that rapid improvements can be achieved 
hopes of huge investment in the former communist nation have not 
yet been realized unemployment is soaring as unprofitable 
businesses and factories close 
he appealed to his guests to send experienced workers to eastern 
germany to provide badly needed knowledge and advice 
kohl said a consensus has to be reached on how to remove 
difficulties facing the reconstruction of eastern germany 
the two germanys united last wednesday and kohl made it clear 
he wants to quickly build up what was formerly east germany and 
give its people a standard of living more in line with that of the 
west 
also on monday interior minister wolfgang schaeuble said former 
highranking east german communist party officials should be 
removed from any key posts they may hold now the newspaper die 
welt reported 
it quoted schaeuble as saying that former communists who were 
once high up and are now again swimming like beads of fat on top of 
the soup should lose their jobs 
his comments follow other news reports that some onetime 
members of east germanys secret police now hold official jobs in 
the new united germany 
schaeuble made special mention of the official trusteeship 
overseeing the privatization of businesses in former east germany 
he said former communist party officials found working there 
would be fired according to die welt 
