<TEXT>
nobody suggests malaysia is in 
danger of breaking up but the ties that bind its outermost states 
to the federation occasionally seem frayed 
rumbles of discontent from sabah and sarawak the territories 
across the south china sea in northern borneo are nothing new 
they are based on vast geographic economic and ethnic differences 
and on pure politics 
grumbling is usually loudest at election time some state 
politicians seek votes by accusing the central government of 
neglect and advocate more autonomy 
in july elections for the 48member sabah state assembly the 
ruling parti bersatu sabah made states rights its focus and was 
returned to power with 36 seats it demanded a larger share of 
federal revenue for sabah and a review of the agreement under which 
the state became part of malaysia in 1963 
four party supporters were arrested during the campaign for 
alleged involvement in a secessionist plot prime minister mahathir 
mohamad tried to cool antifederal rhetoric with the warning if 
this trend is followed in other states our nation will be split 
more than a month after the election information minister 
mohamed rahmat said sabah and sarawak had requested new talks on 
their status in the federation 
the state of the union is still intact mohamed told 
reporters in fact it is getting better we have survived as a 
nation for 27 years and both sarawak and sabah have progressed 
under one roof 
citing the merger of east and west germany and overtures between 
north and south korea he said the time is for unification not 
secession 
most of the problems are rooted in malaysias creation from 
assorted british territories in postcolonial southeast asia 
the 11 peninsular states of what was then malaya gained 
independence in 1957 six years later malaya merged with 
singapore sabah and sarawak to form malaysia 
brunei the oilrich sultanate nearly surrounded by sarawak 
declined an invitation to join 
singapore predominantly chinese was ousted in 1965 because its 
leaders were viewed as a threat to the political control of 
indigenous malays 
sabah and sarawak were granted concessions including control of 
immigration from the peninsula citizens of what is called 
peninsular malaysia need passports to enter the states 
they also counted on an intergovernmental committee to protect 
their interests in kuala lumpur it was supposed to convene every 
10 years to review progress of the outer states but has not met 
since 1973 
there is support for an igc meeting and maybe it will be 
held soon mohamed said 
officials in sabah and sarawak say their special status as 
cofounders of the federation was chipped away over the years each 
wants to be treated as one of three equal partners not one of 13 
states 
i believe the people in sabah and sarawak do not hate 
peninsular malaysians mohamed said they consider us as all in 
one family it is only the politicians 
the borneo states differ markedly from peninsular malaysia 
together they are larger than all 11 western states but their 
population is much smaller 
sarawak has 16 million people sabah has 14 million in a 
national total of 174 million sabahs population inlcudes more 
than 500000 immigrants from the philippines and indonesia most of 
them illegal 
islam is malaysias official religion but sabahs governing 
political party is led by christians 
most malaysians are ethnic malays and there is a sizable chinese 
minority sabah and sarawak have a variety of indigenous tribes 
many of which maintain traditional animistic beliefs 
sabah is one of the countrys richest states because of timber 
oil and natural gas sarawak prospers from exporting tropical 
hardwoods natural gas and pepper 
the two states keep only 5 percent of the revenue from their oil 
and gas exports as royalties and want an increase 
they retain all income from logging and largely ignore appeals 
from kuala lumpur to ban the export of whole logs in addition to 
conserving the tropical forests the federal government wants more 
domestic timber processing which would earn as much money from a 
lower export volume 
some experts say sabah will be logged out by the end of the 
century a report by the international tropical timber organization 
predicts the annual cutting rate in sarawak of more than 13 million 
cubic yards will deplete its remaining virgin forests within 11 
years 
</TEXT>
