<DOCNO> AP901008-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
petro zeleniuch a ukrainian catholic 
priest held services in his village hut for 28 years covering the 
windows so the kgb could not see what was going on 
he was ordained secretly in 1961 by the outlawed greekrite 
church and tended to the spiritual needs of ukrainian peasants on 
the border with poland despite warnings beatings and arrests 
now he ministers legally traveling from village to village 
every sunday and performing pastoral duties during the week in 
jarovov and nearby towns grateful believers crowd around for a 
word or a touch after each twohour service 
less than a year since it was made legal again by order of 
president mikhail s gorbachev the ukrainian catholic church is 
trying to reclaim its confiscated property training new priests 
and benefiting from the rising tide of ukrainian nationalism 
the faithful number more than 45 million according to priests 
and catholic activists many of whom see the church as a key 
element in the movement for independence by the rich populous 
republic 
like other faiths in the soviet union it is expected to benefit 
from legislation approved in principle by the soviet parliament 
sept 26 that forbids government interference in religion 
in jarovov the catholic church is a 260yearold jewel made of 
wood painted harvest yellow and protected by a shiny new steel 
roof whose gleaming crosses stretch toward the sky 
sunday prayers are held behind the church not inside 
scaffolding fills the interior which is being restored and 
renovated 
it has been decades since the building was used as a church 
most recently it was a museum of atheism and religion said 
zeleniuchs daughterinlaw olga 
last year she said zeleniuch and some local men went to the 
communist party secretary demanded the keys and got them theirs 
was among the first successes of ukrainian catholics in winning 
back churches seized 44 years ago 
a greater victory was recorded aug 14 when authorities in lvov 
the main city of the western ukraine returned the baroque 18th 
century cathedral of st george after a year of agitation it was 
the seat of the churchs last metropolitan andrei sheptitsky who 
died in 1944 
the goldencolored cathedral complex and adjoining 
metropolitans palace was transferred in 1946 to the 
statecontrolled russian orthodox church which until then had only 
one church in the city of 770000 people 625 miles southeast of 
moscow 
now a catholic metropolitan is back in the cathedral aided by a 
few priests who formerly worked underground 
one of them the rev zenovi pavlish said he was a factory hand 
for 25 years and changed jobs whenever his bosses discovered his 
real vocation he conducted services in forests or private homes 
and is still getting used to wearing his robes in public 
an estimated 100000 faithful attended the cathedrals first 
catholic service aug 19 and in moscow the russian orthodox 
patriarch was not pleased alexei ii accused ukrainian catholics of 
seizing the cathedral violently and demanded it back 
ukrainian catholic priests deny any use of force 
the return of the cathedral has great meaning said the rev 
roman shafran assistant to the new metropolitan volodimir 
sterniuk it is a symbol that our church exists of its moral 
strength and authority 
pavlish said there will be no going back our nation was on 
its knees now it is standing up 
the ukrainian catholic church was the chief religion of the 
western ukraine a region historically under polish or 
austrohungarian rather than russian 
josef stalin who annexed the western ukraine at the beginning 
of world war ii banned the church in 1946 at about the same time 
his generals were liquidating anticommunist ukrainian partisans 
in the dictators eyes ukrainian catholicism was a bastion of 
nationalism all the more suspect because of its ties to the 
vatican 
some catholic churches were given to the tame russian orthodox 
hierarchy based in moscow others were turned into warehouses 
museums libraries or shops 
priests who did not go underground were arrested and deported to 
labor camps where many died 
beginning in 1987 under gorbachev some ukrainian catholic 
priests came into the open but the church was banned until last 
december gorbachev legalized it just before his historic meeting 
in rome with pope john paul ii 
today officially everything is normal zeleniuch said 
but in practice they still make things difficult for us 
the shortage of priests that is our misery said father 
muzychko an exiled ukrainian catholic official now able to visit 
from rome 
he said the church has only about 750 priests some responsible 
for 10 tp 15 villages and is training 500 more but the first 
ordinations are two years away 
ivan gel an activist in the independence movement rukh and 
deputy leader of the regional legislature said catholics have 
retrieved about 200 churches and want more he said catholics make 
up 70 to 80 percent of christians in the ukraine but have only 20 
to 30 percent of the churches 
these churches were built by the hands of catholics he 
said the russian orthodox church does not want to recognize our 
history 
a new ukrainian orthodox church autonomous from moscow 
complicates matters catholics claim it was established in part to 
compete with their faith 
in some cases three congregations catholic russian orthodox 
and ukrainian orthodox fight over the same church 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901008-0172 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
there is an aspirin for the pain and suffering 
the white house and congressional budget negotiators have inflicted 
on themselves and that is to eliminate wasteful spending 
it is an option frequently ignored except by taxpayers who are 
widely accused of wanting lower taxes while simultaneously refusing 
to accept cuts in medicare social security and similar benefits 
but it is probably more accurate to ascribe to voters a logical 
goal that of cutting wasteful spending rather than the 
contradictory policy of which they have been accused that of lower 
taxes and more spending 
there is hardly a family that doesnt understand the need for 
cutting especially today with recession coming if not here and 
with unemployment rising they have been forced to retrench and 
live within their incomes 
industry has been forced to do the same to the extent that 
downsizing has become a fad word in the business lexicon even 
philanthropic groups have felt the pinch and have reluctantly 
limited their goals 
the same has been asked of government but seldom is there an 
answer 
in 1984 the presidents private sector survey on cost control 
popularly called the grace commission after its chairman j peter 
grace recommended 424 billion in cuts over a threeyear period 
last november the general accounting office found 150 billion 
in program waste fraud and financial mismanagement last spring 
the congressional budget office recommended reforms to yield 
savings of 60 billion in the first year 
as recently as last may the heritage foundation a conservative 
think tank offered a list of 130 billion in cuts that its 
researchers said would cause minimal damage 
some idea of why such cuts arent made came from that latest 
analysis by scott hodge federal budget analyst for the 
foundation he would ask congress to break an addiction to 
deceptive often deceitful porkbarrel spending 
to an aid packgge earlier this year for panama and nicaragua 
for example members of congress tacked on their own special 
interest expenditures for local domestic projects that had nothing 
to do with national interests 
hodge and his researchers cite examples of harmless 
expenditures such as financing a study of the causes of rudeness 
lying and cheating on tennis courts and one seeking to determine 
why people fall in love 
harmless in themselves perhaps so but not in the damaging 
lesson they send that spending is in and saving is out and that 
misusing other peoples money is acceptable so long as they remain 
unaware of it 
besides as members of congress themselves concede a little 
spending oft repeated adds up to a lot that lot can be 
especially crucial to the economy in a recession attended by 
unemployment and bankruptcies 
americans have been made especially aware of tax dangers from 
the lips of president bush whose comments have included the 
statement that when the government raises a dollar in revenues 
congress spends a dollar fifty 
perhaps critics of waste are saying voters arent refusing to 
accept the pain of an austerity budget so much as they are trying 
to tell congress that it must use public money wisely honestly and 
with restraint 
</TEXT>
