<TEXT>
 
editors note in america the group with the most health 
problems gets the least care these are the children of the poor 
in a corner of virginia has appeared a solution which some are 
likening to a miracle cure 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
everybody knows what an ounce of prevention 
is worth but the people in this ageless valley between the blue 
ridge and allegheny mountains are taking yesterdays adage a step 
further 
in todays vocabulary theyre betting that the bottom line on a 
pound of cure is that its also cost effective 
the result is that this valleys poor children up to age 8 
americas neediest have a medical home as the physicians here 
call it that means the children of parents who cant pay may 
nonetheless have a regular doctor of their own choosing whose 
office they can visit regularly for scheduled shots and checkups 
and for unexpected ailments even in the middle of the night even 
on weekends just like the wealthy kids 
these are the children who live below the poverty line and thus 
qualify for medicaid but also children of the working poor who 
dont qualify but still cant afford doctor bills and have no 
medical insurance 
they include for example gerald and roberta mccraw both in 
their 30s who have 5monthold twins angela and amanda and three 
other children under 7 a third generation of children raised in 
poverty 
life was tough enough when gerald was earning minimum wage for a 
37hour week as a nursing home orderly last winter he came down 
with rheumatoid arthritis he worked when he could through spring 
then not at all now he cant even lift his children for a hug 
when one of the kids came down with something a cough an 
earache they went to a hospital emergency room or the twiceaweek 
free clinic or maybe a public health office though it closes at 5 
pm now they go to a doctors office an experience most american 
children take for granted 
i still dont believe this is happening to us roberta was 
saying the other day jiggling a baby girl in her lap i cant 
believe my children are going to grow up healthy have good 
teeth she turned the baby to face her and held her close the 
mothers eyes moistened 
chip is a miracle she whispered i used to not believe in 
miracles but chip is a miracle 
its baptismal name was the comprehensive health investment 
project at age 2 it is now known throughout the valley simply as 
chip it is a cooperative effort of private doctors working with 
the support and machinery of existing social welfare agencies and 
health departments if affording the same level of health care to 
the needy and affluent alike is not a miracle no one in americas 
medical or social establishments seems to know of any other program 
just like it 
what it is says cabell brand chairman of virginias board 
of health is the result of community action the real question 
is can it work elsewhere the answer is of course it can 
no the real question is who pays 
except for some startup cash from a foundation chip runs on an 
artful blend of money for a whole alphabet of programs already 
funded women infants and children wic aid to families with 
dependent children afdc medicaid and others 
suppose a child has a hearing loss and a speech delay says 
peggy balla a public health nurse who became chips director is 
that a medical problem or an educational problem or both you have 
to cut through these narrow areas of concern 
one program for instance covered new mothers until a year 
after the birth that rule had to be changed to shift money to chip 
during the childs critical first year of development a 
bookkeeping problem the money was there all along 
from its first stages of development chips healthy growth 
appears to be ordained 
were already committed says the health boards brand to 
starting chip in four more areas next year eight more the year 
after that 12 more the following year then it will cover all of 
virginia there is no reason for it to stop at the state line 
indeed delegations from 16 other states have visited roanoke to 
have a look a statewide program says brand is in a better 
position to become a line item in the state budget than is a local 
budget 
the 1990 census reveals that 128 percent of americans have 
incomes below the official poverty level of 12675 for a family of 
four a rate worse than 20 years ago and that the children 
continue to be the poorest of the poor more than one in five 
american children 225 percent live in poverty 
it makes no sense said douglas pierce a roanoke 
pediatrician that the group with the most health problems has 
the least access to health care 
that bitter irony continued to nag pierce after he had 
confronted it for three years as president of the virginia 
pediatric society 
medicaid wasnt getting the job done he said here in 
roanoke 42 percent of the people who qualified for medicaid werent 
using it they didnt know they could or didnt understand how to 
go about it 
for whatever reason it didnt much matter because only about 
one doctor in 10 would accept medicaid patients anyhow they would 
give time at the twiceaweek free clinic and make other 
contributions but they wouldnt put up with the medicaid 
frustrations the paperwork the unkept appointments all that goes 
with it that left nearly half the medicaid money unspent and the 
rest spent inefficiently 
and then there were the working poor not sufficiently indigent 
to qualify for medicaid said pierce what about them 
one day in early 1987 pierce saw in the paper that cabell brand 
of roanoke had been appointed to the state board of health 
i knew cabell i had treated his children pierce said so 
i picked up the phone and said cabell something has to be 
done 
pierce called the right person 
cabell brand is known throughout virginia as just that someone 
who gets things done 
he was an early volunteer in lyndon johnsons war on poverty in 
1964 he organized the roanoke valleys community action program 
total action against poverty tap which grew into 29 agencies 
tailored as he says to turning the needy into productive 
citizens of the roanoke valley 
tap is no patchwork of services as is sometimes the case it is 
a coordinated movement tailored to the needs and ways of the 
225000 people of the roanoke valley after one generation it can 
point to a long list of gains in wresting families and individuals 
from the whirlpool of poverty 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901008-0177 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
tap has become a model for antipoverty efforts across the 
nation three of its programs have been lifted whole to other 
states another which brought safe drinking water and toilets 
first to rural homes in the roanoke valley then all of virginia 
eventually moved to washington as a national program 
chip became taps 30th agency it fit right in 
to get it going brand brought together doctors public health 
professionals lawyers tap veterans state and local officials 
everyone we thought could help he said 
we identified the problem and worked out a plausible solution 
the state health department gave us 118000 and we were on our 
way 
they started the program june 16 1988 with pierce the five 
pediatricians in practice with him and 100 patients it went well 
after a year they grew to 300 patients and more doctors that went 
even better six months later the state upped its ante to 200000 
and the wk kellogg foundation of michigan granted 15 million to 
expand further last august kellogg impressed came up with 
another 23 million to spread chip across virginia 
now chip has more than 900 patients enrolled all six of the 
valleys childrens dentists participate and all but three of its 
19 family doctors and 14 pediatricians chip turned down the three 
because they didnt cover on nights and weekends 
we have a ways to go said peggy balla the chip director 
we have identified 4800 potential patients and hope to get them 
all we get more efficient every day weve worked out a lot of 
bugs our computer programs and all our experience will be helpful 
in the replication of chip in other areas 
one of the bugs was getting prescriptions filled the public 
health office which fills them cutrate closes at 5 pm the 
valleys largest drugstore chain now provides 24hour service at 
even lower prices another bug doctor appointments missed for lack 
of transportation a church donated a van 
thats what community action is all about said cabell brand 
its the key to the whole program 
the chip staff includes six public health nurses and six 
outreach workers they work as teams visiting each patient 
regularly at home case management an essential of the whole 
scheme each team has a caseload of about 150 which they agree is 
too many but will improve with more staff 
the nurse has a copy of the same records the doctor keeps she 
sees that his orders are followedmedication given appointments 
kept the main complaints doctors had about the habits of medicaid 
patients 
just convincing the parents that they really do have a doctor 
they can call any time they have a question and persuading them to 
do it even in the middle of the night may be the hardest job of 
all said one nurse connie willet 
but watching the way they light up when they finally come to 
realize they are included in the health care system which most of 
us take for granted is really satisfying sometimes i think their 
newfound self esteem is the best medicine of all 
willets outreach worker teammate darlene brown was able to 
come up with a second bed when roberta mccraw had twins has helped 
her find diapers in an emergency as well as food and clothes the 
five little mccraws also are regular patrons of chips free lending 
library not books toys 
case workers tend to get personally interested in chip families 
one mccraw child now has a good winter coat that darlene browns 
own daughter outgrew another has a coat formerly worn by a child 
of teammate connie willet 
chips doctors get paid at the medicaid rate if the patient 
doesnt quite qualify for medicaid the same rate applies 
qualification in virginia is the same as the federal minimum of 135 
percent of the poverty level but chip stretches that to 150 percent 
to take in the working poor doctors say it covers about 70 percent 
of their regular fees 
but chip does the billing relieves the doctors of medicaid 
paperwork and further makes life easier by sending along with each 
new chip patient a medicalhistory questionnaire already completed 
by the case nurse not to mention seeing to it that his 
instructions are followed and appointments kept 
in the doctors waiting room or in the treatment room 
theres no way to tell a chip patient from any other when its 
time to pay the parent shows a chip card and thats that 
preventive medicine shots checkups what the doctors call 
well care are like fire prevention obviously beneficial but 
hard to measure in dollars how much in future medical bills will 
chip save by giving children a healthy start the childrens 
defense fund a national group says the annual saving is 10 
percent health insurance companies with one eye on that huge 
group of uninsured is keeping the other eye on chip 
we have a chance to do some blowaway things here it seems to 
me said john berry head of blue crossblue shield in virginia 
blue cross has supported chip from the beginning completely 
outfitting the chip office in roanoke with furniture and equipment 
one major financial effect of chip is apparent right now from a 
recent survey of 10000 childrens visits to the roanoke memorial 
hospital emergency room 
it found that nearly half 46 percent were between 3 pm and 
midnight and that fewer than 15 percent were justifiable 
emergency room visits according to dr preston boggess director 
of pediatric education 
in an emergency room with no records of the patient 
available you have to practice defensive medicine boggess said 
that means extensive tests and lab work to cover all the 
possibilities 
they are mostly unnecessary always costly and take time from 
real emergencies but some people have no place else to take a sick 
child 
roberta mccraw has 
the baby was fussing and running a fever and i was scared to 
death she said 
i had never called my doctor at night and didnt know whether 
i should maybe just go ahead to the emergency room 
but i called and he said bring her in 
it wasnt my doctor but was one in the same building it as 
his turn to work that night 
he examined her and looked at her records and in a minute 
said mrs mccraw amandas teething take her home shell be 
just fine 
and she was 
