editors note when a woman goes to prison often it is her 
family that suffers the most and here in a remote corner of west 
virginia near the federal prison for women at alderson there is a 
group that cares at the alderson hospitality house friends and 
loved ones of women behind bars can find food and lodging and a 
sympathetic ear 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
once a month joe gump leaves his home in 
bloomingdale mich and drives all night to visit his wife here in 
the allegheny mountains of rural west virginia 
gump is a 62yearold retired chemical engineer and businessman 
his wife jean gump is a 63yearold inmate at the 
minimumsecurity federal prison camp of alderson serving eight 
years for helping trash some missile silos in missouri during an 
antinuclear protest in 1986 
as a result of his monthly visits gump has found a home away 
from home in this remote town of 1000 people where the federal 
prison which holds about 800 women is the biggest industry 
hes a regular at the privately funded alderson hospitality 
house which opened in 1977 to provide lodging and meals for 
friends and families of prisoners the first of its kind in the 
nation 
the threestory white house built in 1889 as a boarding house 
has 11 guest rooms and two bathrooms to house up to 35 people 
including children it is operated by dee and john vodicka strong 
advocates of prisoners rights 
you put someone in prison to punish them for a crime but 
youre really punishing the people they leave behind says joe 
gump 
in their case thats a lot of people joe and jean gump raised 
12 children 
and theyre the kind of people the vodickas want to help 
these families are us given the same circumstances mrs 
vodicka says that saying there but for the grace of god go 
i is so true we learn that every weekend 
most of the inmates at the alderson prison are blacks or 
hispanics from big cities most serving time for drug offenses or 
tax evasion faye pollard an assistant to the warden estimates 
that 60 percent of them are mothers 
what cost is prison wreaking on the children mrs vodicka 
asks what is their future fifteen or 20 years down the line 
that anger is going to need to be handled 
the vodickas feel most of the prisoners should be sentenced to 
home confinement work release and drug rehabilitation 
i think the vast majority of women here could be let out today 
with no effect on society vodicka says there are few women up 
here who have committed heinous crimes like you read about they 
have offended society by breaking laws but they could have been 
diverted short of prison 
she cites the gump case 
jean gump and four friends entered a nuclear missile site at 
knob noster mo on good friday 1986 and attacked the silos with 
sledgehammers she poured her own blood on the silo and then the 
five waited 45 minutes for the police to arrive and arrest them 
after jean went to prison joe got involved with civil 
disobedience he used the same tools and banners that jean used 
when he staged his own protest in 1987 on the day the atomic bomb 
was dropped on hiroshima 
he got a different judge and was sentenced to two years in 
prison 
but alderson also has been home to some notorious offenders 
including lynette squeaky fromme and sandra good disciples of 
charles manson convicted in the sharon tate murders and sarah 
jane moore fromme and moore tried to assassinate president gerald 
ford just 17 days apart 
moore and fromme were transferred to other prisons after they 
tried to escape and are serving life sentences good was paroled in 
1985 
john vodicka 42 is no stranger to prisons he worked as a 
chaplain for the san francisco bay area county jails as a prison 
rights advocate in new orleans and in a program for the homeless in 
atlanta before moving to west virginia 
alderson house has a 26000 budget and receives no federal 
funding vodicka says about half the money comes from guests and 
the remainder from private or church donations 
there are few frills 
none of us receives a salary practically all of it goes back 
into the house for upkeep and utilities vodicka says food and 
maintenance are the big items 
furniture is donated by churches and individuals guests often 
bring food instead of money 
visiting children play with the vodicka children gabriel 5 
and luke 2 and samuel born sept 12 
the large kitchen table has several highchairs around it 
colorful alphabet magnets an arms length away on the 
refrigerator are a big draw to the children who like to spell out 
their names and leave messages 
the vodickas share the chores volunteers frequently live with 
them 
the vodickas are the third couple to run the house dick dieter 
and maggie louden opened the hospitality house in 1977 basing 
their philosophy on the roman catholic worker movement of the 1930s 
and 1940s the movement emphasized a simple lifestyle based on 
pacifism and helping those in need 
after another couple ran the house for two years the vodickas 
took over in 1986 
just to the right of the houses front door is the office from 
which the vodickas coordinate guest lists and compile three 
newsletters that promote their views against the death penalty and 
for prisoners rights they live in two private rooms behind the 
office 
now the vodika family is looking for someone to take over the 
house with their new addition to the family they are outgrowing 
the two small rooms 
every time the house has need someone or something it has 
come through mrs vodicka says 
