<TEXT>
robert urich best known as a streetwise 
detective moves away from the urban battleground in a new tv 
comedy series american dreamer he plays a modern philosopher 
in a small town 
the nbc show offers a mixture of humor introspection 
remembrances and fantasy focusing on urich who portrays a former 
network journalist seeking a new life after his wife is killed by a 
terrorist while they are on assignment together 
the tv reporter quits his highpaying highprofile job to move 
his son and daughter to a small town to write a weekly 
humaninterest column his new assistant played by carol kane 
says human interest oh you mean fluff each episode becomes 
a meandering odyssey as he explores his innermost thoughts en route 
to arriving at his column 
the way he thinks about things is the nut of the show urich 
says in an interview at his home on the edge of the hollywood 
hills the writing of a column can be a catalyst for him to 
explore some personal experience the column is his life and his 
life is the column 
in a novel a writer can take a chapter to examine a 
characters feelings we can do it in a snap by having him step 
into limbo the stage suddenly goes black except for the spotlight 
on him were experimenting with different lighting techniques the 
limbo is a chance for us to not complete scenes but to let him 
explain what happened or recreate a scene from his past 
despite more than a decade in toughguy roles urich sees 
american dreamer as a return to his roots 
i started out on the straw hat circuit doing father of the 
bride and all that stuff he says when i came to la the 
first thing i did was bob amp carol amp ted amp alice i was told it 
was comedy and its difficult you have to read i said wait 
thats what i do for a living then i was in soap and tabitha 
so its familiar yet different 
the way they work here is amazing you dont have a finished 
script when you start out at least 80 percent of its rewritten 
its an exploration by the actors and writers the writers listen 
and watch and finetune it finally by the end of the week youve 
got it down when the audience comes in its like opening night 
the writers and producers dress up send flowers and come in ready 
to have a good time 
the shows from gary david goldbergs ubu productions which 
last did family ties 
