when guitarist pat metheny discovered a few open dates on his 
calendar last december he hooked up with two other jazz veterans 
drummer roy haynes and bassist dave holland and headed for the 
studio 
their goal was a good time rather than a record but when 
metheny played back the tapes of their eighthour session he liked 
what he heard and decided to release some of the music as 
question amp answer 
sad to say methenys enthusiasm was misplaced there isnt much 
to hear here as always he coins some nice melodies and then takes 
them in interesting directions the lovely reflective change of 
heart is comparable to his best work 
but while metheny is often spinning intricate sounds his rhythm 
section detracts and distracts haynes always a busy drummer is 
annoying with his incessant cymbals its as though he was being 
paid by the ching hollands bass is undermixed and mumbles most of 
the time especially on the fast tunes and when he solos 
another reason the 62minute record seems longer is that its 
dynamically flat as metheny points out in the liner notes he 
played one guitar at one setting throughout his synclavier on the 
closing three flights up provides the records only change in 
texture 
metheny has released only two other trio albums so his fans may 
regard question amp answer as a treat but its not for the 
fainthearted 
by steven wine associated press writer 
equals 
