<TEXT>
americans will get a rare glimpse of how 
one japanese art collector viewed western art when a collection of 
60 impressionist and modern paintings goes on exhibit next sunday 
shojiro ishibasi founder of bridgestone the worlds third 
largest tire manufacturer began collecting artwork before world 
war ii only once before has any part of the collection left tokyo 
and that was in 1962 when works traveled to paris 
bridgestone has two tire plants in tennessee and had its 
american headquarters in the state until it merged with firestone 
and moved to arkon ohio 
masterworks paintings from the bridgestone collection will 
hang in the tennessee state museum through jan 20 the exhibit 
features works by nearly every major painter of the impressionist 
school and includes claude monets twilight venice and amedeo 
modiglianis portrait of a young farmer 
its one japanese collectors view of western art tennessee 
state museum curator lois riggins ezell said some did not paint 
in the impressionist style but they all began painting in that 
time period and were all influenced by the school of 
impressionism 
the museum has booked tours from new york and the midwest since 
bridgestone probably will not let the exhibit travel again ezell 
said 
highlights include wellknown paintings such as water 
lilies from the later works of monet and the outstanding mont 
saintvictoire and chateau noir by paul cezanne 
cezanne spent half of his life painting his mountain and this 
is one of the best ezell said 
works by henri rousseau paul gauguin and henri matisse provide 
a look at impressionism moving into modernism 
the collection also includes modern paintings such as pablo 
picassos cup and spoon and giorgio de chiricos 
troubadour 
cup and spoon is a still life in cubist style while 
troubadour is a painting of a mannequin one of the types of 
work for which chirico is best known 
the 60 paintings were selected primarily by the curators of the 
tokyo museum as the most artistically significant and the most 
stable ezell said paintings by toulouselautrec and chagall were 
considered two fragile for shipment and work by rembrandt van rijn 
was painted on a board which lacks the resiliency of canvas and 
does not travel well 
the collection will be on display through jan 20 1991 and will 
then return to japan 
