<TEXT>
florence harrison nesbit has spent 60 years 
trying to shake the image of a lady flower painter 
at 80 nesbit still slips on a smock for painting binges at 
her studio in seattles queen anne neighborhood she creates amid a 
stack of canvasses that includes watercolors of whidbey island and 
walla walla and scenes of her old sun porch in berkeley calif 
a shoebox of note cards keeps track of a lifetime of paintings 
some are sold some are displayed at seattles bayview manor where 
the artist lives many are forgotten 
a port angeles gallery manager recently scouted nesbit for a 
showing of her work are you just a flower painter he asked 
skeptically she bristled at the remark 
its a stigma you cant get rid of nesbit said we want 
to paint just as badly as men do most of us have had the same 
training as men had but we have an awful time finding a place to 
show 
seattle gallery owners david martin and dominic zambito want to 
change all that 
this month the martinzambito fine art gallery on capitol hill 
is mounting an exhibition of paintings by northwest women to 
commemorate the 60th anniversary of the women painters of 
washington 
the show will display works primarily from the 1930s 40s and 
50s by nesbit and more than a dozen other members of the womens 
painting group only five of the artists featured are still alive 
relegated to family archives or sometimes destroyed altogether 
art from this generation of northwest women has not been easy to 
assemble martin said hes rounded up works from families friends 
and some of the painters themselves a few paintings were picked up 
at new england auction houses 
while critics continue to praise the vision of northwestern 
painters mark tobey kenneth callahan and morris graves lesser 
known painters have been lost in history martin said this show 
he said attempts to give northwest women artists the recognition 
they deserve 
it just seems unbalanced martin said they are as 
talented as their male counterparts who showed in museums and 
gallery retrospectives i want people to come and see their artwork 
because its very good 
the exhibition is a travelogue of washington state countrysides 
and cityscapes paintings are priced from the high hundreds to 
6500 
dorothy milne rising offers 1940s scenes of the puyallup fair 
and seattles pike place market rising 95 currently lives in 
mukilteo 
cle elums oldest homestead from the 1930s is portrayed by olive 
malestrom carl there are paintings of mount shuksan by elizabeth 
warhanik and eastern washington haystacks by dorothy dolph jensen 
two founders of the women painters of washington 
the exhibit also includes an 80yearold photograph by myra 
wiggins another cofounder one of the photo secessionists 
wiggins participated in a landmark photography exhibition with 
alfred stieglitz in new york in 1910 a picture from that show will 
be on display at the pike street gallery 
perhaps the best known artist featured is yvonne twining humber 
82 of seattle a painter for the works progress administration 
wpa in boston in the 1930s humber sells more art work in new 
england than the pacific northwest martin said but the strength 
of her painting is apparent in an ethereal depiction of the 
cascades at night and her lively carnival scenes her work will 
be exhibited in a onewoman show this december at the 
martinzambito gallery 
the circus fascinated me said humber at her home in the 
citys magnolia neighborhood old circuses would have a tent with 
elephants wandering around it was the informality there was loads 
of life 
a northwest resident since the 1940s humber said she has never 
been a flower painter job opportunities not sexual politics 
directed her vision and she said her early experience with the wpa 
was influential 
i paint buildings with better composition than i do fuzzy 
little trees the artist explained it was just circumstance 
that pushed me in that direction but i loved it 
humber says she experienced no discrimination as a woman 
painter but regrets her sexsegregated art training at the 
national academy of design in new york 
femaleonly classes however were better than no school at all 
after a divorce in 1967 nesbit applied to the fine arts program 
at her alma mater the university of washington she hoped to earn 
a masters degree after completing one year of studies at scripps 
college in california but she was turned down by the program 
director an old college classmate who flatly told her that uw was 
not enrolling women painters 
in those days before womens lib we didnt think about it 
we just took it nesbit recalled i almost gave up painting and 
that was my life 
nesbit was an early success placing first in watercolor in 1933 
at the seattle art museums northwest annual exhibition in the 
decades that followed she won several painting awards and exhibited 
at a number of onewoman shows in california and seattles frye art 
museum 
employed as a wpa painting teacher in the 1930s nesbit later 
got a job drawing fashion figures for newspaper advertisements she 
cofounded the northwest watercolor society in 1940 
when she can nesbit still takes to the outdoors to paint live 
landscapes but with age confining her more to the art studio she 
has begun experimenting with new techniques such as tilttop 
painting 
like other talented women artists of her generation nesbit 
followed her passion but was rarely encouraged to take it 
seriously after six decades of perfecting her art she still 
stumbles in labeling herself a professional painter 
my sister worked at boeing for 27 years and that was 
considered successful i was just a painter messing around 
nesbit said 
financially i couldnt exist from what i make from my 
painting emotionally i couldnt have lived without it 
</TEXT>
