evocative pictures of the juke joints 
imes a white southerner whose work appears in the museum of 
modern art was referring generally to black culture which he said 
he was only vaguely aware of before attending an integrated 
high school in the 1960s 
when i began photographing six or seven years later he 
adds it was in part my wish and my need to overcome this 
ignorance that helped make my choice of subject an obvious one 
beginning by photographing people and scenes in rural 
mississippi he eventually came to see the juke joints as subjects 
the result is juke joint university press of mississippi 
3995 
the collection of 61 color photographs provides outsiders with a 
tantalizing look into these clubs which beckon and forbid when one 
passes them on a country road their strings of yearround 
christmas bulbs give off firefly light their doors may open 
momentarily to release a yellow glow and a thudding bluesy beat 
its the photos capacity to be other than cultural 
snapshots that novelist richard ford appreciates the 
mississippian author of the sportswriter analyzes the 
pictures uncanny art in an introductory essay 
still the peek in the jukes door the view of these private 
places that the pictures offer is an undeniable part of the books 
value 
thats partly because in some cases the places depicted no 
longer exist beyond that details in the corners of photographs 
help flesh out the lives of the mostly unseen juke joint patrons 
signs on the wall often handwritten reflect the local sense of 
humor or the approach here to problems seen everywhere o lord 
please help me keep my damn nose out of other peoples business 
says one sign and next to it no dope please crack will kill 
you look at your buddy hes dead you no 
in the homely decorations of many clubs that imes portrays any 
reader quickly glimpses the notorious poverty of the region as 
well as its legendary creativity 
some photos focus closely on brightly spraypainted interiors or 
homemade furniture on a cracked wall of the riverside lounge in 
shaw miss somebody painted a large floating bull in a style 
that strangely recalls the art of the cave paintings of france and 
spain 
what i see in imes photographs does not equal the human 
condition ford writes only a human condition a miniature 
advanced as art and meant to ease the adjustments between ourselves 
and the world by offering beauty consolation diversion the 
satisfaction of direct address all the usual enticements by which 
art dignifies and pleases us 
its risky to suggest where art originates but part of what 
compells a reader to these pictures of places that are anything but 
glamorous comes from the light the photographer captures in one 
photograph a golden sunrise or sunset light bathes the torn 
tarpaper wall of the pink pony cafe in darling miss and makes 
shadows all in profile of a line of people just outside the 
frame 
the simultaneous presence and absence of people in many of the 
photos is another reflection of imes art some interior shots were 
exposed and printed so that furnishings such as a pool table 
appear in sharp focus while patrons such as moving pool players 
appear as blurs almost as ghosts 
no one is seen in a claustrophobic shot of a bands instruments 
speakers amplifiers and even drink glasses but the reader almost 
hears the din of conversation between sets 
here and elsewhere in this collection the unknown as ford 
says seems to have been put to use 
 
editors note christopher sullivan is aps southern regional 
reporter based in atlanta 
</TEXT>
