<TEXT>
shortly after the ussoviet business weekly 
commersant hit the newsstands in january government ministers 
started calling editorial offices to find out how to muzzle its 
sharp commentaries 
when they found out we were independent they kind of lost 
their bearings and gave up said vladimir yakovlev commersant 
editorinchief 
commersant and two other new soviet periodicals owe their 
independence in part to the policy of glasnost or openness and in 
part to their backing from investors in the united states and other 
western countries 
unlike most soviet publications they are not affiliated with 
the communist party or government and are not subject to the same 
hierarchical pressures that soviet bureaucrats are accustomed to 
applying 
commersant backed by the us investment company refco is the 
type of soviet business that a visiting delegation from the new 
york stock exchange will be scrutinizing during a threeday meeting 
in moscow this week 
the tabloid provides a weekly barometer of the ups and downs of 
foreign enterprises performances in the soviet union and critical 
features on soviet economics 
although paper shortages have forced the government newspaper 
izvestia to miss editions twice commersant has a supply contract 
with a private company guaranteeing a steady flow of newsprint 
its russian circulation is 350000 and its english distribution 
is 30000 yakovlev said commersan recently went on sale in the 
united states 
according to officials of the state committee for the press 
joint ventures have filed 23 applications to start publications 
sixty applications have been filed by private individuals and 20 by 
political parties and public organizations the officials said 
two glossy magazines moscow and business in the ussr are 
building their circulations and several pilot publications have 
appeared 
izvestia and hearst publications published a pilot issue of a 
new englishrussian newspaper on july 4 and hope to be issuing a 
regular edition next year the weekly magazine business week 
brought out a dual language edition last summer and also hopes to 
publish regularly 
special onetime editions of western magazines including ladies 
home journal and paris match also have appeared in soviet shops 
other joint venture magazines include new farmer an offshoot of 
the usbased rodale press that could distribute in the soviet 
union next year to give soviet farmers american agricultural 
knowhow and russian business review a quarterly to be published 
in 1991 by a swisssoviet joint venture 
business in the ussr is aimed at the emerging class of 
soviet business leaders said editor vadim biryukov 
we want to hit the right guy the economist the factory 
director the banker the small businessman anybody who deals 
with the economy he said 
until recently the term businessman was disparaging 
biryukov said we are trying to change that we clearly see all 
our readers we talk to them try to give them the courage to 
become businessmen to be proud to be a businessman 
in a step designed to open the door for jointventure 
publishing the supreme soviet parliament adopted a press law aug 
1 under the law a new pubication can start after an application 
is filed and a regestration fee of 2000 3200 is paid in hard 
currency 
that could pose a problem for biryukov who founded the magazine 
earlier and may end up paying twice 
we registered before the law was adopted now we have to 
register again he complained we havent had time to earn that 
kind of money 
business in the ussr published its sixth issue in october 
with a circulation of 100000 editions in russian and 50000 in 
english the magazine relies heavily on advertising for hard 
currency revenues 
moscow magazine is patterned after the trendy glossy 
publications that thrive in big american cities 
we are styled a little after city magazines like new york 
said editor derk sauer a dutchman 
but we are not a copy of new york they are a lifestyle 
magazine and theres not a lot of lifestyle here in moscow he 
said 
