<TEXT>
britains longdelayed entry into europes 
exchange rate mechanism could spur the european communitys move 
toward economic and monetary union but for margaret thatcher the 
immediate motives are closer to home analysts say 
linking the pound to other european currencies should stabilize 
the pounds exchange rate help fight inflation and bring down 
interest rates which could improve the prime ministers chances of 
winning a fourth consecutive term 
but the price of joining the socalled erm could be a further 
crimp on an already slowing economy and a rise in unemployment 
the government announced friday it would link the pound to the 
mechanism on monday the government also said britains 15 percent 
interest rates would come down a full percentage point the same 
day 
under the mechanism britains currency will be allowed to 
fluctuate no more than 6 percent from an agreedupon exchange rate 
putting a floor under the pound gives mrs thatcher room to cut 
high interest rates unpopular with both homeowners and businesses 
before she must call an election by mid1992 
it was becoming urgent for the government to get interest 
rates down if they were going to stop the next election being lost 
on the recession issue robin aspinall analyst at the london 
investment firm hoare govett ltd 
britain already is in a mild recession the business community 
and opposition labor party say no it isnt the government 
argues 
mrs thatcher likes a strong pound because it adds up to tighter 
monetary policy it fights inflation by forcing companies to keep 
export prices competitive by keeping wages and other costs down 
but as a strong pound forces export prices higher it becomes 
harder for british companies to compete overseas corporate profits 
can fall and jobs can be lost 
yes erm would impose a small discipline for bringing 
inflation down but it does so at the expense of growth said 
avinash persaud a monetary economist at the london investment firm 
ubs phillips and drew 
britain becomes the tenth of the 12 european community 
currencies to enter the exchange rate mechanism currencies of 
britain and spain are allowed to flucutate 6 percent from the 
agreed rate and the others are allowed to swing 225 percent in 
either direction still outside the mechanism are the portuguese 
escudo and greek drachma 
central banks of erm member countries are required to buy or 
sell currencies to keep the exchange rate within the prescribed 
band 
the erm is intended to provide stable exchange rates that make 
business planning easier and reduce disruptions to economic 
strategies of the ec and its member states 
after years of pressure from erm advocates mrs thatcher in 
june 1989 promised to join once british inflation fell closer into 
line with the ec average of 55 percent and once capital flowed 
freely in europe 
britain has decided to join even though inflation stands at 106 
percent because the rate is headed downward mrs thatcher said 
friday she has kept interest rates at 15 percent for a year to 
fight inflation by slowing consumer demand 
the fact that our policies are working and are seen to be 
working have made both these decisions possible she said 
entering the mechanism would underpin our antiinflationary 
stance she said 
britain said the pound would enter the erm at a rate of 295 
german marks 
by entering britain fulfilled its commitment to the first part 
of a threestage plan for the economic and monetary union of the ec 
nations 
but while spurring monetary union the move also strengthened 
mrs thatchers hand in fighting the next two stages a single 
currency and central banking system 
it will make the path easier said geoffrey dicks who 
teaches at the london business schol but it also will give the 
uk a stronger base from which to launch its serious criticisms 
instead of a single currency britain has proposed turning the 
european currency unit into a 13th common european currency to be 
used alongside the existing 12 ec currencies 
</TEXT>
