<DOCNO> AP901008-0203 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here in questionandanswer form is an 
explanation of europes exchange rate mechanism or erm 
what is the erm 
it is a feature of the european monetary system that limits the 
fluctuations of european community currencies 
why was it set up 
it was set up in march 1979 to prevent disruptive exchange rate 
swings the fixed exchange rates which had supported european 
economies since world war ii had broken down and the floating rates 
were creating havoc for the 12nation community 
who belongs to the erm 
with newly joining britain 10 ec countries still to join are 
portugal and greece 
how does the erm work 
the erm limits how much the currencies can move up or down 
against one another most of the members observe a margin of 225 
percent above or below agreed rates but britain and spain use a 6 
percent band which gives their governments more breathing space 
how do countries keep their currencies within those bands 
central banks intervene buying or selling currencies or 
changing their interest rates 
does it always work 
no sometimes inflation or other economic conditions threaten to 
push a currency beyond its band when that happens the members 
realign the system by mutual agreement changing the basic rates of 
one or more currencies to relieve the pressure there have been 14 
rate or band realignments since 1979 the last was on jan 8 when 
italy switched from the 6percent to the 225 percent band 
does the erm affect european exchange rates against the dollar 
it has no direct bearing on these currencies values against 
nonec currencies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

