<DOCNO> AP901008-0217 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
christopher sinclairstevenson a courteous old 
etonian in the tough world of british publishing broke away to set 
up on his own after 28 years with one company and struck gold with 
his first book 
sinclairstevenson ltd sold 60000 copies of a life of 
everpopular charles dickens in less than two weeks at 1995 pounds 
3770 each the sales sent dickens to second place on the 
sunday times bestseller list behind a book on cricket 
but what shook the book trade was the large sum of 650000 
pounds nearly 13 million offered by the fledgling independent 
publisher to peter ackroyd an admired writer who tackled dickens 
after doing other literary lives some in novel form 
it was an unusually large amount of money but ackroyd has a 
good reputation and track record and the offer also covers a book 
he is writing about william blake the publisher said 
sinclairstevenson 51 talked in the office he set up with a 
staff of 10 in a charming kensington mews 
he launched his company and the dickens book sept 3 just over 
a year after leaving the respected hardback publishing house of 
hamish hamilton his only employer since he left cambridge 
university with a modern languages degree his last 15 years with 
the firm were spent as managing director 
he didnt like the changed atmosphere when the firm which had 
earlier been sold to the canadabased thomson group was sold again 
to penguin the giant paperback publisher 
from friends and contacts he raised 24 million pounds 45 
million to start his own company when authors whose books he 
edited found he was leaving they went with him including ackroyd 
sinclairstevenson is steering clear of paperback publishing 
and a large slice of ackroyds advance came from selling the 
paperback rights in dickens to other companies sales of the 
hardback should comfortably make up the balance he said 
the new publishers first catalog is half fiction and the rest 
mostly travel memoirs and contemporary history wellknown writers 
such as paul theroux an wilson and jk galbraith are on the 
list and of the 27 books 20 are by authors from his old 
employers 
he handled most of the hamish hamilton authors who were 
finalists over the years for the booker prize the literary event 
of the year in britain 
most people thought william boyd who was a finalist in 1982 
with an icecream war should have been nominated again this year 
for brazzaville beach which we submitted we will be in some 
difficulty next year deciding which three of our novelists to put 
in the publisher said 
publishing is big business total book sales in britain were 
worth 22 billion pounds 41 billion last year book exports 
amounted to a further 655 million pounds 12 billion 
the industry is dominated by about a dozen companies among 
them macmillan the oxford and cambridge university presses and 
harpercollins and news international which belong to media magnate 
rupert murdoch 
publishing has changed vastly from the days when it was 
considered a leisurely occupation for gentlemen revered imprints 
have disappeared while others cling to their identities in the 
embrace of multinationals and conglomerates 
i think publishers take over other publishers to stop other 
publishers taking them over when they become big they want to be 
strongly based everywhere sinclairstevenson said 
a big organization has clout in the marketplace it can afford 
expensive authors has more power in dealing with bookshops and a 
bigger presence in the publishing world he said 
corporate life is very different to that of an independent 
publisher i began to feel the imperatives in the penguin group 
were systems rather than books 
editors are concerned with publishing and selling but 
conglomerates keep looking at their internal affairs they work to 
dotted lines call meetings and tell people what to do their 
authors get missed out he said 
when i left in july 1989 a lot of the authors i was handling 
were my personal friends and i suppose they thought i was a good 
publisher and would do their future books well i think they felt 
that once id gone their connection with hamish hamilton ceased 
they wouldnt know anyone there 
writers are important sinclairstevenson said they lead 
rather lonely lives they are not going to an office every day and 
they need encouraging to write and to live as well i like to 
publish authors i know and like i find it difficult to publish 
authors i dont like 
he thinks the spate of mergers isnt good for publishing 
it concentrates too much power in too few hands narrows the 
choice for the author and reduces the contact between the author 
his agent and the publishers he said i think we did dickens 
as well as any conglomerate and possibly better because its our 
lifeblood 
we are hungrier he said we have no fat to live off 
</TEXT>
