<TEXT>
stock market and foreign exchange traders 
responded enthusiastically monday to britains sudden entry of the 
pound into the mechanism that regulates most european currency 
exchange rates 
british homeowners were optimistic that chancellor of the 
exchequer john majors simultaneous announcement friday of a 1 
percent drop in interest rates could signal a turnaround from two 
years of economic gloom 
the exchange rate mechanism erm of the european monetary 
system links european currencies to avert huge swings in exchange 
rates with british membership 10 of the currencies of the 
12nation european community are linked in the system 
portugal and greece still have not added their currencies bank 
of portugal governor jose tavares moreira said monday that portugal 
would not be rushed into the system despite britains entry 
there had been speculation in the market friday that the escudo 
could follow the pound 
under the rules of ems membership the british government must 
halt any rise in the pound outside its upper band of 313 german 
marks to the pound 
sterling is allowed to range within 6 percent of its central 
rate of 296 so its lowest exchange rate is 277 marks 
if the currency goes too high britain must lower its exchange 
rate either by selling sterling or reducing interest rates 
britains entry to the ems boosted the pound to 303 marks on 
monday from 299 at fridays close on the foreign exchange markets 
the dollarpound exchange rate is not directly affected by 
britains entry into the system but the pound soared against the 
dollar monday on concerns about the us economy and the lack of a 
plan for budget deficit cuts in the united states currency dealers 
said 
the pound rose in london to 19745 from 19455 late friday and 
in new york to 19760 from 19525 
economists said entry into the system wont be a panacea but 
said it was long overdue 
weve joined a club we should have been in for quite some 
time said trevor cass foreign exchange manager at barclays de 
zoete wedd over the last five years we have seen the european 
economies benefiting from erm the uk wants a slice of that 
